# Substrate-wide shellcheck configuration
# Phase-1-alpha/0a — codifies the substrate's intentional shell patterns
# so warning-severity gates focus on real fragility (SC2044, SC2206, etc.)
# rather than mechanical noise from the codebase's deliberate idioms.

# SC2034: variable appears unused
#
# Disabled at project level because the substrate's smoke-test harnesses
# (tests/smoke-h{4,7,8,ht}.sh + tests/smoke-library-*.sh) use the
# `command || VAR=$?` pattern to capture exit codes without immediately
# branching on them. This is intentional — the captured exit code is
# inspected in subsequent assertions or logged for diagnostic purposes.
# Example pattern (well-established across ~30 sites):
#
#   T68_OUT=$(some-command 2>/dev/null) || T68_EXIT=$?
#   # T68_EXIT may be read by a downstream assertion or just kept for
#   # forward-compat diagnostic capture
#
# Forcing SC2034 compliance would require either:
#   (a) mechanical `_` prefix on ~30 variables (noise; no semantic value)
#   (b) per-site `# shellcheck disable=SC2034` directives (clutter)
# Project-level disable documents the substrate's stance and keeps the
# warning-gate focused on load-bearing fragility classes.
#
# If a future contributor introduces a TRUE unused-var bug, they should
# remove the assignment entirely — not rely on this disable as cover.
disable=SC2034
